land","Baddesley Clinton, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom":"Baddesley Clinton, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"James","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name borne in the New Testament by two of Christ's disciples, James son of Zebedee and James son of Alphaeus. This form comes from Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of <i>Iacobus</i>, Latin form of Greek <i>Iakobos</i>. This is the same name as Old Testament   Jacob   (Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>), but for many centuries now they have been thought of in the English-speaking world as two distinct names. In Britain, <i>James</i> is a royal name that from the beginning of the 15th century onwards was associated particularly with the Scottish house of Stewart:  James I  of Scotland (  1394–1437 ; ruled  1424–37 ) was a patron of the arts and a noted poet, as well as an energetic ruler.  King James VI  of Scotland (  1566–1625 ; reigned  1567–1625 ) succeeded to the throne of England in  1603 . His grandson,  James II  of England (  1633–1701 ; reigned  1685–8 ) was a Roman Catholic, deposed in  1688  in favour of his Protestant daughter Mary and her husband William of Orange. From then on he, his son (also called James), and his grandson Charles (‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’) made various unsuccessful attempts to recover the English throne. Their supporters were known as Jacobites (from Latin <i>Iacobus</i>), and the name James became for a while particularly associated with Roman Catholicism on the one hand, and Highland opposition to the English government on the other. Nevertheless, it has since become one of the most perennially popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":31,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":40,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When James Bisege was born in 1184, in Warwickshire, England, his father, Ralph Bisege, was 54 and his mother, Mrs. Ralph Bisege, was 52. He had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Matilda. He died on 6 May 1236, in Ullesthorpe, Leicestershire, England, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1184–6 May 1236":"1184–6. mai 1236","1184–1236":"1184–1236","1180–1250":"1180–1250","1210–1238":"1210–1238","1210–1278":"1210–1278","–Male":"Surnud","1130–Male":"1130–Surnud","1132–Female":"1132–Surnud","1238":"1238","1215":"1215","1236":"1236","1224":"1224","1278":"1278","1210":"1210","1132":"1132","1130":"1130","1184":"1184","1250":"1250","6 May 1236":"6. mai 1236","1180":"1180","Ullesthorpe, Leicestershire, England":"Ullesthorpe, Leicestershire, England","Kingsbury, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom":"Kingsbury, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Baddesley, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Baddesley Clinton, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom":"Baddesley Clinton, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1184–6 May 1236":"1184–6. toukokuuta 1236","1184–1236":"1184–1236","1180–1250":"1180–1250","1210–1238":"1210–1238","1210–1278":"1210–1278","–Male":"Kuollut","1130–Male":"1130–Kuollut","1132–Female":"1132–Kuollut","1238":"1238","1215":"1215","1236":"1236","1224":"1224","1278":"1278","1210":"1210","1132":"1132","1130":"1130","1184":"1184","1250":"1250","6 M